layout: layouts/service-subpage.njk
title: "Federal Employee Benefits Planning | Capital Wealth"
description: "Specialized retirement planning for federal employees. FERS optimization, TSP management, FEGLI analysis, FEHB coordination, and more. Nationwide fiduciary service from Lehi, Utah."
serviceTag: "federal"
breadcrumbs:
  - { name: "Home", url: "/" }
  - { name: "Services", url: "/services/" }
  - { name: "Federal Employee Benefits", url: "/services/federal-benefits/" }
faqSchema:
  - question: "What makes Capital Wealth different from other federal benefits advisors?"
    answer: "We are fee-only fiduciaries — we don't sell insurance products or earn commissions from seminars. Mike Stevens has spent his career exclusively focused on the federal benefits system, and our planning process covers the full picture: FERS pension optimization, TSP strategy, FEGLI analysis, FEHB coordination, Social Security timing, and tax planning. Most seminar presenters are licensed to sell annuities. We're licensed to give advice."
  - question: "When should I start planning for federal retirement?"
    answer: "Ideally, five years before your target retirement date. A five-year runway lets us model Roth TSP conversions, optimize your high-3 salary average, evaluate FEGLI reduction options, and coordinate your retirement date with Social Security and Medicare eligibility. That said, we help federal employees at every career stage — even those who retired years ago and want a second opinion on their benefit elections."
  - question: "Do you offer a free consultation for federal employees?"
    answer: "Yes. We offer a complimentary 30-minute introductory call where we review your current situation, identify the biggest gaps in your federal benefits strategy, and outline what a full planning engagement would look like. There's no obligation and no sales pitch — just an honest conversation about whether we're the right fit."
  - question: "Can you help federal employees outside of Utah?"
    answer: "Absolutely. We work with federal employees and retirees nationwide via secure video conferencing. Whether you're stationed at a military base in Virginia, a VA hospital in Texas, or a federal office in D.C., our planning process works the same way. About half of our federal clients are outside Utah."
  - question: "How is fee-only planning different from the free seminars agencies offer?"
    answer: "Free federal retirement seminars are typically sponsored by insurance companies. The presenters earn commissions when attendees purchase annuities or life insurance products after the event. Fee-only planning means you pay us directly for advice — we have no products to sell and no incentive other than giving you the best recommendation. Our advice is legally required to be in your best interest."
